LEGISLATURE OF THE STATE OF IDAHO
Sixty-eighth Legislature First Regular Session - 2025
IN THE HOUSE OF REPRESENTATIVES
HOUSE BILL NO. 156
BY JUDICIARY, RULES AND ADMINISTRATION COMMITTEE
1 AN ACT
2 RELATING TO THE IDAHO COMMISSION OF PARDONS AND PAROLE; AMENDING SECTION
3 20-1002, IDAHO CODE, TO REVISE A PROVISION REGARDING THE COMPENSATION
4 OF COMMISSIONERS; AND DECLARING AN EMERGENCY AND PROVIDING AN EFFECTIVE
5 DATE.
6 Be It Enacted by the Legislature of the State of Idaho:
7 SECTION 1. That Section 20-1002, Idaho Code, be, and the same is hereby
8 amended to read as follows:
9 20-1002. COMMISSION CREATED -- APPOINTMENT -- QUALIFICATIONS -- TERMS
10 -- MEETINGS -- COMPENSATION -- EXECUTIVE DIRECTOR AND STAFF. (1) There is
11 hereby created the Idaho commission of pardons and parole. The governor
12 shall appoint seven (7) commissioners, subject to the advice and consent of
13 the senate.
14 (2) Commissioners shall serve at the pleasure of the governor and not
15 more than four (4) commissioners shall be from any one (1) political party.
16 (3) Terms on the commission shall be for three (3) years, and vacancies
17 in the commission for unexpired terms shall be filled by appointment by the
18 governor for the remainder of the term. Commissioners may be reappointed for
19 subsequent terms.
20 (4) The commission and the board may meet as necessary to exchange such
21 information to enable each to effectively carry out their respective duties.
22 (5) The commission shall meet at such times and places as determined to
23 be necessary and convenient, or at the call of the executive director, and in
24 any event no less than quarterly.
25 (6) Two (2) commissioners may meet to make decisions on the disposition
26 of parole violations. Such decisions must be unanimous, and in the event
27 they are not unanimous, then the parole violation disposition decision will
28 be made by a majority of the full commission either at the next quarterly
29 meeting or special meeting.
30 (7) Three (3) commissioners may meet to make decisions to grant or deny
31 parole. Such decisions must be unanimous, and in the event they are not unan-
32 imous, then the decision to grant or deny parole will be made by a majority of
33 the full commission at the next quarterly meeting.
34 (8) Commissioners shall be compensated as provided by section
35 59-509(i), Idaho Code, when attending quarterly meetings conducted at a
36 date and time separate from a hearing session or other meetings approved by
37 the executive director. Commissioners shall receive compensation of three
38 hundred dollars ($300) four hundred dollars ($400) per commissioner per day
39 when conducting parole, commutation, pardon, revocation or other hearings
40 and shall be reimbursed for actual and necessary expenses subject to the
41 limitations provided in section 67-2008, Idaho Code.

2
1 (9) The governor shall appoint the executive director for the commis-
2 sion. The executive director shall be the full-time employee who shall re-
3 port to, serve at the pleasure of, and be compensated as determined by the
4 governor. The executive director shall be the official representative for
5 the commission, shall be responsible for the managing and administration of
6 daily commission business, shall assist the commission in carrying out all
7 of its duties and powers as prescribed by law, and shall schedule business
8 meetings and hearing sessions at times convenient to the commissioners. For
9 each scheduled session, the executive director shall designate one (1) of
10 the commissioners as the presiding officer for conducting the hearings. The
11 executive director may hire such staff and employees as are approved by the
12 governor. The executive director shall also have such other duties and re-
13 sponsibilities as the governor shall assign.
14 SECTION 2. An emergency existing therefor, which emergency is hereby
15 declared to exist, this act shall be in full force and effect on and after
16 July 1, 2025.

